le properly.\n\nActually, let me reconsider meet-in-the-middle more carefully. The proper version:\n\n1. Split n buttons into two halves L and R (not free vars, but ALL buttons).\n2. For each of the 2^|L| combinations of left buttons, compute the resulting light state and store (state, weight, button_set).\n3. For each of the 2^|R| combinations of right buttons, compute the required remaining state (target XOR right_state) and look up in the left hash.\n4. Find the combination with minimum total weight.\n\nWait, this doesn't use the null space at all. It's a direct approach on the original problem. With 40 buttons, |L| = 20, |R| = 20. 2^20 = 1M entries for each half. And for each right entry, we look up the matching left entry. Total: 2^20 + 2^20 = 2M computations.\n\nThis is the standard meet-in-the-middle approach for subset sum / XOR problems. It should be very fast for 40 buttons!\n\nLet me implement this approach directly, bypassing the Gaussian elimination for the toggle case.\n\nWait, but 2^20 entries each having a 40-bit state... we need a hash map from state to (min_weight, lex_info). For 2^20 = 1M entries, this is fine.\n\nAnd for the counter case with modulus p: each of the p^20 combinations... for p = 2, that's 2^20 = 1M. For p = 97, that's 97^20 which is astronomically large. So meet-in-the-middle on the original problem doesn't work for the counter case.\n\nSo my plan:\n- **Toggle case**: Use meet-in-the-middle on the original problem (split 40 buttons into two halves of 20).\n- **Counter case**: Use Gaussian elimination + optimization over free variables (the current approach works since p^F with p ≤ 97 and F potentially large needs the algebraic approach).\n\nFor the counter case, what's the maximum F? With 40 buttons and 40 lights, F = 40 - rank. If rank = 40, F = 0. With p = 97, p^F needs to be manageable. If F ≤ 4, then 97^4 ≈ 88M which is borderline. If F > 4 with p = 97, we need a smarter approach.\n\nFor the counter case with large p and many f